It would be curious to note that in the deeply philosophical Slavic languages, the word for monster - "—á—É–¥–æ–≤–∏—â–µ" - comes from the word "miracle" ("—á—É–¥–æ"), which is also used for "wonder".

A monster is, literally, a creature of MIRACLE, a creature of WONDER.

Compare this to the vulgar current English interpretation, in which a monster just means something ugly/horrifying.

It castrates the concept of a monster from meaning and turns it into nothing but a living scarecrow. 

God created great whales, God created miraculous wonders.

I agree with Chesterton on this: in Christianity you are only supposed to fight your opponent if you are weaker than him.

"And Cain said unto the LORD, My punishment is greater than I can bear."

Poor Cain, how can we not feel bad for him? Imagine how lost he must have been in those early years of creation, how confused when the Lord did not accept his offering? He was filled with fear and panic.
When we talk how he carried evil in his heart, we ought to remember that so do we. In his place we would have fallen into the same sin. We ought to learn from his fall, and to remember.
And yet we brought even worse sins in the form of the nuclear bomb. Are we not worse than Cain?
